{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bb450024-8cd0-44bc-b3cb-92be30f319f0","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                        # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the trace out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView** (Windows), or convert to speedscope format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **debug/sidecar container** or the `dotnet-monitor` sidecar image.\n- For production, consider deploying **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar — it exposes an HTTP API to collect traces on demand without exec.\n- 30 seconds is usually enough to capture a representative sample under high CPU.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"19dc835a-8280-4143-aea2-f4b5b94cce6b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":419,"requestId":"1B83:1DE8C5:ECAFF7:10B9576:6A0281D5"},"id":"64d6c850-517f-4ccd-a834-87c324678d4c","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:26:56.082Z","parentId":"3ff18881-ee6b-4e0c-b1d7-080679e6376b"}
